<p>I decided to make a scarf using the advent yarn held together with some lovely DK acrylic yarn I had in my stash (Deramores Studio DK in ‚ÄòSilver‚Äô). I put the mini skeins into a bag and pulled them out one at a time, randomly working colours as they were picked. I used a 6mm hook and a simple c2c (corner to corner) stitch pattern to create my scarf. I have written the pattern up below, it‚Äôs a great way to use your advent yarn or mini skeins you have in your stash.</p>

<p>A yarn advent calendar was a real treat for me, they are not cheap and I took advantage of Vicki‚Äôs payment plan option in order to spread the cost. Keep an eye out for information on yarn advent calendars around the middle part of the year, most indie dyers give you plenty of notice so you save your pennies and treat yourself.</p>

<h2 id="2019-advent-scarf-pattern"><strong>2019 Advent Scarf Pattern</strong></h2>

<h3 id="you-will-need">You will need:</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Mini skeins in various colours (I used 24 x 10g DK minis)</li>
  <li>DK yarn in a neutral colour (I used 250g Deramore Studio DK in ‚ÄòSilver‚Äô)</li>
  <li>6mm crochet hook (go down a hook size if you are using 4ply mini skeins)</li>
  <li>Piece of thick card to make the tassels.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="terms">Terms:</h3>

<ul>
  <li>ch ‚Äì Chain</li>
  <li>tr ‚Äì Treble crochet (US Double Crochet)</li>
  <li>ss ‚Äì Slip Stitch</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="pattern">Pattern:</h3>

<p>To make the scarf you will be using the c2c or Corner to Corner crochet technique. You can find lots of tutorials online if you are not used to this method, I have included the link to one of the best tutorials I have found ‚Äì <a href="https://makeanddocrew.com/how-to-corner-to-corner-crochet-c2c-for-beginners/">https://makeanddocrew.com/how-to-corner-to-corner-crochet-c2c-for-beginners/</a></p>

<ol>
  <li>Using your first mini skein and strand of DK yarn held together make 5 tassels.</li>
  <li>You are now going to work a c2c rectangle which is 8 blocks wide, using your DK yarn held together with your mini skeins. Use up the remaining yarn from your first mini skein and then pick one at random every time you run out.</li>
  <li>When you reach your last mini skein make 5 more tassels to match the first set of 5 made, then finish your scarf with the remaining yarn. By making the tassels at these points you will know you have enough yarn for them.</li>
  <li>Sew in all of your ends and then attach 5 tassels evenly across each end of your scarf.</li>
</ol>

